&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence from London 
[normal]TravelWatch
[normal] and Passenger Focus (SLC 005)
[normal]1.  London 
[normal]TravelWatch
[normal] and Passenger Focus are the official consumer watchdogs for users of the main line, metro, light rail and tram networks in 
[normal]England
[normal] and 
[normal]Wales
[normal], and of the main line railways in 
[normal]Scotland
[normal].    In 2011/12 about 2.8 billion passenger trips 
[normal]were made on these systems.
[normal]2.  Both organisations are members of the Parliamentary Advisory Committee on Transport Safety (PACTS) and are represented on its Rail Safety Working Group, which proposed this topic.  We are therefore pleased that the Select Co
[normal]mmittee has chosen it as a topic for an inquiry.
[normal]3.  Our evidence below relates solely to the main line railways operated by Network Rail.  There are comparatively few level crossings on the other rail systems within our remit, and most of these are on tra
[normal]mways which operate mainly on line of sight (i.e. without signals), in some cases on-street, and present a different profile of risk.
[normal]4.  The paper comprises an introductory note on the level and pattern of risk presented by level crossings, followed by a 
[normal]comment in reply to each of the questions listed by the Committee.  It concludes with some suggested recommendations.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Level crossing risk in context[bold]&#xa0;[bold]5.  Risk on the rail network is measured in terms of fatalities and weighted injuries (FWI), a composite 
[normal]statistic which applies weightings to injuries of varying severity in order to equate these to fatalities.  For details of the methodology, see table 1 in RSSB (formerly the Rail Safety &amp; Standards Board)’s 
[normal]Annual Safety Performance Report 2012/13
[normal], 
[normal]from wh
[normal]ich
[normal] 
[normal]most of the other data cited in this note are drawn.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.  The industry’s risk profile is continuously updated by RSSB by means of the safety risk model, which is derived from the data captured by the industry-wide safety management information system (
[normal]SMIS) in which all rail operators are required by their licences to participate.  Risk presented by 
[normal]trespassers, suicides and suspected suicides is
[normal] excluded from the following statistics.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.  The model shows that the total current annual FWI rate associat
[normal]ed with level crossings is 10.7, of which all but 1.1 is represented by fatalities.  Of the total, 9.5 is risk to members of the public, 1.0 is to passengers and 0.2 is to members of the railway workforce.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.  Most of the risk arises from individuals bein
[normal]g struck by trains while using crossings (6.6), followed by road vehicles being struck by trains (3.2), with much lesser amounts associated with slips/trips/falls (0.5) or individuals being struck by road vehicles or crossing equipment  (0.1). 
