[normal]9.  Risk arising from level crossings accounts for 11% of total railway risk.  In terms of the three categories of people 
[normal]exposed to it, it represents only 2% of the risk faced by passengers and 
[normal]1% of that faced by the workforce, but 71% of that faced by non-trespassing members of the public (who in this context are mainly road and path users).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10.  
[normal]Data collected by the Eur
[normal]opean Rail Agency (ERA) relate only to fatalities and to accidents involving moving trains, and are normalised 
[normal]by train kilometres run.  
[normal]By this more restricted definition, Britain has the lowest level of risk of any of the European Economic Area member st
[normal]ates which have railways (i.e. excluding Cyprus, Iceland and Malta), with an average during 2009-11 of 19 level crossing fatalities per billion train kilometres, compared with an EEA average of 260 [see ERA’s 
[normal]Intermediate report on the development of railw
[normal]ay safety in the European Union 2013
[normal]].  Care should be taken in making such comparisons, because the level of risk is heavily dependent on the density and type of crossings on the network, and the volume and speed of both rail and road (or foot) traffic ov
[normal]er them.  Nevertheless, it is encouraging that 
[normal]Britain
[normal]’s crossing safety performance appears to bear comparison well with other similar rail systems.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.  Since most casualties occurring at level crossings are suffered by pedestrians, cyclists or the occu
[normal]pants of road vehicles, it is arguable that level crossing risk is best considered in the context of the overall safety of travel by road (or on footpaths), rather than by rail.  In the past decade, about 0.2% of fatalities suffered by road vehicle users h
[normal]ave occurred at level crossings, but in the case of cyclists, motor cyclists and pedestrians, this proportion rises to about 0.5%.  When weighted to reflect the distances travelled by each mode (i.e. per billion passenger/ pedestrian kilometres), the risk 
[normal]to other road/path users is about 50 times greater than to vehicle users [data derived from the Department for Transport’s 
[normal]Transport Statistics Great Britain 2012
[normal]].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]12.  In the light of these statistics, it could be argued that for most road and rail user
[normal]s, level crossing risk is minimal, and resources expended on mitigating it further would deliver greater returns if they were directed elsewhere.  But a number of points should be borne in mind.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]13.  The Committee has listed seven issues on which evidence is specifically 
[normal]sought.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Are current safety measures at level crossings adequate?  How should they be improved[bold]? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14.  In common with all employers, Network Rail has a legal duty to conduct its business in such a manner as to reduce risks to health and safety so far as is “reasonably practicable”.  Taking account of court rulings over the years, the rail industry has 
[normal]produced guidance (see RSSB’s manual on 
[normal]Taking safe decisions
[normal])
[normal] to assist its members in interpreting this obligation.  To put the matter at its simplest, the legal duty does not (and cannot) require the total elimination of risk, but rather that it should 
[normal]be controlled at a level at which the cost, time and effort required to do so are not in “gross disproportion” to the safety benefits secured.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]15.  There is no single, simple test of the adequacy of crossing safety measures, and they can only properly b
[normal]e judged in the context of the physical and usage characteristics of individual sites.  But Network Rail has been a world leader in the development of crossing risk modelling to inform its decisions, and its overall crossing safety performance compares fav
[normal]ourably with that of any other equivalent rail network in Europe.  So while there is always scope for further improvement, and lapses can and do occur from time to time, the industry’s achievements and current performance should not go unacknowledged.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]16.
[normal]  The range of possible improvements currently being deployed 
[normal]includes :
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In addition to bridges and [bold]underpasses what other cost-effective measures can be introduced to replace or improve safety at level crossings?[bold]17.  Short of outright closure, grade-separation (i.e. replacing crossings by bridges or underpasses) is the only means of ensuring that the r
[normal]isks associated with crossings are eliminated.  That is why the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR), the industry’s safety regulator, no longer allows new crossings to be opened, other than in wholly exceptional circumstances, and does not permit line speeds o
[normal]n existing routes to be raised above 125 mph without all crossings being removed.  But such infrastructure improvements (even if they are designed only for use by pedestrians) invariably cost hundreds of thousands – if not millions – of pounds, and it is o
[normal]nly at very high-risk crossings that such expenditure is likely to pass the test of “reasonable practicability” and thus be cost-effective on grounds of its safety benefits alone.  
[normal]18.  However, where both rail and road traffic densities are high, crossin
[normal]gs can cause extended delays to road vehicles and generate significant traffic congestion.  Logically, the economic impact of this congestion should be factored into the appraisal of crossing improvements.  In practice, this seldom happens, because in Brit
[normal]ain – unlike some other countries – the entire cost of crossing upgrades or replacements is usually borne by the railway, and highway authorities are under no obligation to contribute towards the cost of infrastructure improvements even if its primary purp
[normal]ose is reduce risk and delay to road users.  This apportionment of the cost burden is an historical anomaly which is overdue for correction.  Crossing-related costs should be borne equally by both the railway and the road authority, and where identifiable 
[normal]costs arise directly from (e.g.) development of land leading to higher vehicle or pedestrian 
[normal]usage,
[normal] these should be recoverable from those responsible.
[normal]19.  Several means of improving crossing safety are listed in response to the preceding question.  Other
[normal]s include providing open or user-worked crossings with barriers, and/or installing telephones (to signallers) at gated crossings which do not yet have them, and/or fitting warning lights and audible alarms at footpath crossings to alert users to the approa
[normal]ch of trains, and/or installing obstacle detectors at automatic crossings to allow half-barriers to be replaced with full-barriers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How should expenditure on improving safety at level crossings be prioritised in relation to other demands on the rail budge[bold]t?[bold]20.  In order to optimise the allocation of its investment and maintenance budgets, Network Rail should apply a common appraisal yardstick both to level crossing schemes and to other 
[normal]projects, including those with a specific safety objective.  If the go
[normal]vernment believes that there are legitimate societal concerns that justify a higher level of expenditure on crossings than this would provide, then it should allocate earmarked funding for this purpose.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]21.  In practice, this approximates to the current a
[normal]rrangements. Network Rail is required by the Health &amp; Safety at Work etc Act 1974 (HSWA) 
[normal]to reduce
[normal] risk so far as is reasonably practicable
[normal], as part of its day-to-day role as the owner, operator and maintainer of the infrastructure of the national rail sys
[normal]tem.  It does this 
[normal]through, for example, 
[normal]its 
[normal]routine risk assessment
[normal]s and its
[normal] renewals and enhancements programmes. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]22.  Every five years, the Secretary of State for Transport (in respect of England and Wales) and Scottish Ministers are required to publi
[normal]sh their desired high level output specifications (HLOS) for the railways, and a statement of the public funds which will be available (SOFA), in the next “control period”.  In response, Network Rail sets outs its strategic business plan, itemising what it
[normal] intends to deliver for the level of funding indicated.  It then falls to the ORR (as the industry’s economic regulator) to determine whether the plan represents an efficient and effective use of resources, and to specify in more detail the required output
[normal]s.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]23.  This process provides ample opportunities for all three parties (government, industry and regulator) to review Network Rail’s record and policies towards safety in general and towards level crossings in particular, and to assess the scope for fu
[normal]rther improvements alongside all of the competing claims on the allocated funds.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Is Network Rail giving sufficient priority to improving safety at level crossings?[bold]24.  In 2010 to 2012, Network Rail achieved a 20% reduction in crossing-related risk.  The two governments’ combined SOFAs for Control Period 5 (i.e. 2014-19) made provision for £75 million of ring-fenced funding to be devoted specifically to further enhan
[normal]cements in crossing safety.  
[normal]25.  In response, in its strategic business plans for this period, published in January 2013, Network Rail has set itself 
[normal]a target of reducing 
[normal]level crossing risk
[normal] by a further 8
[normal]% over the control period
[normal]. 
[normal] This target may at first sight appear low in the light of its recent achievements, but it is important to remember that as the most cost-effective schemes are implemented, so the rate of return on further schemes diminishes, and additional increments in s
[normal]afety improvement become more expensive to deliver.
[normal]26.  The intention is to use this ring-fenced funding to close 30 particularly high-risk crossings and to install a further 200 enforcement cameras, as well as replacing whistle boards with train-detectio
[normal]n equipment and providing additional telephones, miniature warning lights, power-operated gates and improved decking.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]27.  Network Rail’s published policy statement on managing crossing safety commits it, inter alia, to
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]28.  No organisation, least of all Network Rail, is perfect in every respect – as periodic reports from the Rail Accident Investigation Branch bear witness.  But there is clear evidence of a 
[normal]corporate desire further to improve its record on level crossing safety, which is already superior to that of most comparable rail systems. This is a not inconsiderable achievement, and one for which it deserves due recognition.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Is Government policy and [bold]regulatory action by the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in relation to safety at level crossings adequate?  What more should the Government and ORR do?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]29.  
[normal]The government has not sought in recent years to involve itself directly in the detail of rail sa
[normal]fety policy.  But in its July 2012 HLOS statement, it asserted that “
[normal]The Secretary of State specifically wishes the industry to reduce the risk of accidents at level crossings. 
[normal] 
[normal]In accordance with advice from ORR she has made a ring-fenced provision of 
[normal]£65m over CP5 to facilitate the achievement of this outcome by enabling Network Rail to invest to reduce risk.
[normal]”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]30.  
[normal]The equivalent statement by Scottish Ministers, published the previous month, announced the establishment of a
[normal] separate
[normal] £10 million level 
[normal]crossings fund.  This would be made 
[normal]available,
[normal] it was stated, 
[normal]“
[normal]in addition to the baseline funding requirement for level crossing safety in Scotland
[normal], to support Network Rail, local a
[normal]uthorities and other local stakeholders to work in partnership to facilita
[normal]te the closure of level crossings in Scotland.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]31.  No similar provision was made for any other facet of rail safety.  Both governments have therefore acknowledged the priority to be given to level crossings in the industry’s overall safety enhancement p
[normal]rogramme.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]32.  In its 
[normal]Draft determination of Network Rail’s outputs and funding for 2014-19
[normal] (published in June 2013 and subject to public consultation until October this year) the ORR proposes that 
[normal]“
[normal]Network Rail should provide us with its plan to maximise
[normal] the reduction in the risk of accidents at level crossings in CP5 and using the ring-fenced fund, before March
[normal] 
[normal]2014. 
[normal] 
[normal]We ex
[normal]pect the ring-fenced fund to 
[normal]be :
[normal] 
[normal](a)
[normal] 
[normal]used to deliver the maximum risk reduction irrespective of geographical location
[normal] 
[normal](England, Scot
[normal]land and Wales);
[normal] 
[normal](b)
[normal] 
[normal]retained as a central fund; and
[normal] 
[normal](c)
[normal] 
[normal]used across the whole level crossin
[normal]g portfolio.  
[normal]The delivery of the planned package of projects in CP5, to achieve the maximum reduction in risk of accidents at level crossings using the £67m ring-f
[normal]enced fund is a
[normal] 
[normal]regulated output
[normal].”
[normal]  
[normal]It adds that “t
[normal]he risk redu
[normal]ction achieved by using the ring
[normal]-fenced level crossing fund is in addition to reducing risk so far as is reasonably practicable through, for example, routine risk assessment and the renewals 
[normal]and enhancements programmes.
[normal]”
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]33.  ORR’s 
[normal]Health &amp; Safety Report 2013 
[normal]notes that “
[normal]Network Rail is committed to reducing level crossing risk 25% by 2019 and it is currently on-target, as
[normal] 
[normal]measured by its own model, to deliver this. 
[normal] 
[normal]This improvement has com
[normal]e through strong leadership from senior managers and demonstrates what can be achieved with the right focus
[normal].”  However, the report goes on to record that “w
[normal]e found that in the routes,
[normal] 
[normal]some level crossing risk assessments were poor and did not identify the 
[normal]best risk controls. We also found that risk assessments were
[normal] 
[normal]not always being carried out at the right stage of the renewal and enhancement process, which introduced delays and additional costs at the
[normal] 
[normal]level crossing commissioning
[normal] 
[normal]stage.
[normal]  
[normal]We note that Netwo
[normal]rk Rail has recently introduced route
[normal]-
[normal]level crossing managers and a national level crossing team, which should improve the quality of the risk assessment process.
[normal]”
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]34.  
[normal]ORR has summarised its policy on level crossings in the following 
[normal]terms :
[normal]“
[normal]Great Britain’s level crossing safety record is among the best in the world, but every incident has the potential for significant human and economic loss. 
[normal] 
[normal]Level crossings are the single biggest source of railway catastrophic risk, but overall the risks ar
[normal]e well managed. 
[normal]“
[normal]We seek to influence 
[normal]dutyholders
[normal] and others to reduce risk at Britain’s level crossings. 
[normal] 
[normal]We do this through a variety of means ranging from advic
[normal]e to formal enforcement action…  
[normal]Risk control should, where practicable, be achieved through the elimination of level crossings in favour of bridges, underpasses or diversions. 
[normal] 
[normal]Where elimination is not possible, we aim to ensure that duty holders reduce risk 
[normal]so
[normal] far as is reasonably pract
[normal]icable and in accordance with the principles of protection.
[normal]“As the safety regulator for Britain’s railways, our role is to provide clear advice and enforce relevant legislation – including that which relates to level crossings.  We also exercise delegated
[normal] powers of the Secretary of State in making level crossing orders under 
[normal]the 
[normal]Level Crossings Act 1983
[normal].
[normal]“We believe that it is neither effective nor efficient for onl
[normal]y rail companies to be responsible for managing safety at level crossings.  Decisions about level crossings should involve rail companies, traffic authorities and other relevant organisations as early on as possible. 
[normal] 
[normal]Relevant authorities should recognise 
[normal]the wider benefits that safety improvements at level crossings (for example, replacing them with bridges) can bring about, particularly for road users.  If wider benefits can be achieved, the appropriate funding bodies should agree on how the costs of maki
[normal]ng safety improvements will be met. 
[normal]“We are also committed to helping people understand the importance of the 
[normal]safe use of level cro
[normal]ssings
[normal].”
[normal]35.  
[normal]In
[normal] furtherance of the last of these policies. ORR has published a more detailed statement of its 
[normal]Policy on level crossings
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]together with a guide for road (and path) users on 
[normal]Using
[normal] level crossings safely 
[normal]and a technical manual entitled 
[normal]Lev
[normal]el Crossings: a guide for managers, designers and operators
[normal]. 
[normal]  
[normal]It is evident that enhancing crossing safety occupies a central place in ORR’s regulatory strategy.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How should the legislation governing level crossings be updated?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]36.  
[normal]In June 2008
[normal] the two Law Commissions (i.e. for England &amp; 
[normal]Wales,
[normal] and for Scotland) announced that at the suggestion of ORR they would jointly be conducting a review of level crossing law.  The exercise has proved complex and time-consuming, and the Commissions’ final p
[normal]roposals are not now due to appear until later this autumn.  There has, however, been an extremely thorough process of public consultation as part of the review, to which Passenger Focus and London 
[normal]TravelWatch
[normal] have contributed fully.  We do not wish to pre
[normal]-empt the outcome of the Commissions’ work, but we anticipate that it is likely to encompass recommendations relating to (inter alia
[normal]) :
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How should public awareness o[bold]f safety at level crossings be improved?[bold]37.  
[normal]There are a number of different 
[normal]target audiences, and the communications strategy must be tailored to their circumstances.  They include, for 
[normal]example :
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]38.  International Level Crossing Awareness Day, promoted by the International U
[normal]nion of Railways, provides an annual opportunity to run co-ordinated awareness-raising events across the network, to maximise the impact of their message.
